\begin_layout Paragraph
introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This paper reviews an alternative to the efficient markets approach that
 we and others have recently pursued，the approach rests on two assumptions：
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
First, some investors are not fully rational and their demand for risky
 assets is affected by their beliefs or sentiments that are not fully justified
 by fundamental news.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Second, arbitrage — defined as trading by fully rational investors not subject
 to such sentiment — is risky and therefore limited.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Our case for the noise trader approach is threefold.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
First, theoretical models with limited arbitrage are both tractable and
 more plausible than models with perfect arbitrage.
 The efficient markets hypothesis obtains only as an extreme case of perfect
 riskless arbitrage that is unlikely to apply in practice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Second, the investor sentiment/limited arbitrage approach yields a more
 accurate description of financial markets than the efficient markets paradigm.
 The approach not only explains the available anomalies, but also readily
 explains broad features of financial markets such as trading volume and
 actual investment strategies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Third, and most importantly, this approach yields new and testable implications
 about asset prices, some of which have been proved to be consistent with
 the data.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
